They alternatively may descend from [[Kibitsuhiko-no-mikoto]] who roughly ruled [[Okayama Prefecture]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Plutschow |first=Herbert E. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fiJTyA6FsMsC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA12&dq=%22Kibi+clan%22&hl=en |title=Japan's Name Culture: The Significance of Names in a Religious, Political and Social Context |date=1995 |publisher=Psychology Press |isbn=978-1-873410-42-4 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Plutschow |first=Herbert |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AYX7AQAAQBAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PP15&dq=%22Kibi+clan%22&hl=en |title=Matsuri: The Festivals of Japan: With a Selection from P.G. O'Neill's Photographic Archive of Matsuri |date=2013-11-05 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-134-24705-9 |language=en}}</ref>

[[Kibidera]] in [[Sakurai]] is the clan temple of the clan.<ref>{{Cite book |last=McCallum |first=Donald F. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yY4BEAAAQBAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA100&dq=%22Kibi+clan%22&hl=en |title=The Four Great Temples: Buddhist Archaeology, Architecture, and Icons of Seventh-Century Japan |date=2008-11-30 |publisher=University of Hawaii Press |isbn=978-0-8248-6473-6 |language=en}}</ref>

== Kibitsu Shrine ==
The [[Kibitsu Shrine (Bitchū)|Kibitsu Shrine's]] rites are closely linked to its history. It was first made for the Kibi clan. The shrine's gods are the Kibi clan's ancestors who have become gods. These ancestors protect the Kibi area.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book |last=Hardacre |first=Helen |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nunQEAAAQBAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA239&dq=%22Kibi+clan%22&hl=en |title=Marketing the Menacing Fetus in Japan |date=2023-09-01 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0-520-92204-4 |language=en}}</ref>{{Rp|page=239}}

The shrine started as a place for the Kibi clan. It has the clan's ancestors as gods. This gives the shrine a pure and protective feel. The ancestors are seen as good and helpful spirits. This is how the shrine connects with chigo/mizuko. Chigo/mizuko means the souls of babies who died early or were not born.<ref name=":0" />{{Rp|page=239}}

The shrine places the chigo shrine next to the ancestor shrine. It also uses running water. This setup has several meanings:<ref name=":0" />{{Rp|page=239}}

# The water purifies the souls of chigo/mizuko. Mizuko is linked to water.<ref name=":0" />{{Rp|page=239}}
# Being near the ancestor shrine suggests these souls become kind and protective spirits.<ref name=":0" />{{Rp|page=239}}
# As protective spirits, the chigo/mizuko guard those who remember them.<ref name=":0" />{{Rp|page=239}}

This way, the Kibitsu Shrine uses its ties to the Kibi clan. It creates a respectful place for chigo/mizuko. It links them to the shrine's ancestral and protective gods.<ref name=":0" />{{Rp|page=239}}

The Kibitsu Shrine is an important historical site. It became popular in ancient times. The Kibi clan, who started the shrine, used to rule the area. They got the land from the court. Emperor Go-Shirakawa made the shrine the main place for his Department of Divinity. This was during the Jingikan period. But in the Kamakura period, things changed. The shrine's land was given to the [[Ninna-ji|Ninnaji]] temple. Because of this, many small temples were built in the shrine area.<ref name=":0" />{{Rp|page=282}}

During the Tokugawa era, the shrine's land became smaller. However, it still got a special land grant from the shogunate. This grant was for 160 koku of rice every year. There was a busy market near the shrine. People also visited teahouses and inns there. Inside the shrine area, there was a theater and a place for prostitutes. The shrine was a busy place along the [[San'yōdō|San’yodō highway]]. This continued until the [[Meiji Restoration]]..<ref name=":0" />{{Rp|page=282}}

== Harima Fudoki ==
The story of [[Emperor Keikō]] and Inami-no-Wakiiratsume in the [[Harima Fudoki]] shows the relationship between the Kibi clan and the [[Yamato Kingship]]. It suggests that the [[Inami]] area was once a border between the Yamato and Kibi regions.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book |last=Palmer |first=Edwina |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rWzsCgAAQBAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA71&dq=%22Kibi+clan%22&hl=en |title=Harima Fudoki: A Record of Ancient Japan Reinterpreted, Translated, Annotated, and with Commentary |date=2015-11-09 |publisher=BRILL |isbn=978-90-04-26937-8 |language=en}}</ref>

Inami-no-Wakiiratsume, a woman from Inami, is mentioned in several ancient texts. She is thought to be the younger sister of Oiratsume from the "Kojiki,". She might have been a queen in Harima.<ref name=":1" />

The Harima Fudoki does not mention Otarashihiko/Keiko as an emperor. Instead, Otarashihiko might have been a local leader in the Inami district of the Harima coast.<ref name=":1" />

== Decline ==

In 713, at the suggestion of ''Bizen-no-kami'' Nanten - and ''Bizen-no-suke'' Kamitsukeno-no-Kenji the  Eita, Katsuta, Tomata, Kume, Mashima, and Oba districts of [[Bizen Province]] were separated into a new province, and, and Kamitsukeno-no-Kenji was appointed as the first governor of Mimasaka. This separation was the final stage of the disintegration of the former [[Kingdom of Kibi]], and was intended to further weaken the {{ill|Kibi clan|ja|%E5%90%89%E5%82%99%E6%B0%8F}} by putting its iron resources directly under the control of the [[Yamato dynasty|Yamato government]].<ref>[http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/images/uploads/EOS070712Ab.pdf "Nationwide List of ''Ichinomiya''," p. 3] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130517061440/http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/images/uploads/EOS070712Ab.pdf|date=2013-05-17}}; retrieved 2012-11-20.</ref>

== In Popular culture ==
The Kibi clan features in [[Age of Empires (video game)|Age of Empires]] as an enemy faction alongside the [[Izumo clan]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Russell |first=Lawrence T. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IMDmDVRF7o0C&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22Kibi+clan%22&q=%22Kibi+clan%22&hl=en |title=Age of Empires: Unauthorized Game Secrets |date=1997 |publisher=Prima Pub. |isbn=978-0-7615-1053-6 |language=en}}</ref>

