The shrine started as a place for the Kibi clan. It has the clan's ancestors as gods. This gives the shrine a pure and protective feel. The ancestors are seen as good and helpful spirits. This is how the shrine connects with [[Mizuko kuyō|mizuko]]. [[Mizuko kuyō|Mizuko]] means the souls of babies who died early or were not born.<ref name="hardacre-2023a" />{{Rp|page=239}}
The shrine places the [[Mizuko kuyō|mizuko]] shrine next to the ancestor shrine. It also uses running water. This setup has several meanings:<ref name="hardacre-2023a" />{{Rp|page=239}}
# The water purifies the souls of [[Mizuko kuyō|mizuko]]. [[Mizuko kuyō|Mizuko]] is linked to water.<ref name="hardacre-2023a" />{{Rp|page=239}} # Being near the ancestor shrine suggests these souls become kind and protective spirits.<ref name="hardacre-2023a" />{{Rp|page=239}} # As protective spirits, the [[Mizuko kuyō|mizuko]] guard those who remember them.<ref name="hardacre-2023a" />{{Rp|page=239}}
This way, the Kibitsu Shrine uses its ties to the Kibi clan. It creates a respectful place for [[Mizuko kuyō|mizuko]]. It links them to the shrine's ancestral and protective gods.<ref name="hardacre-2023a" />{{Rp|page=239}}
== Harima Fudoki == The story of [[Emperor Keikō]] and Inami-no-Wakiiratsume in the [[Harima Fudoki]] shows the relationship between the Kibi clan and the [[Yamato Kingship]]. It suggests that the [[Inami, Hyōgo|Inami]] area was once a border between the Yamato and Kibi regions.<ref name="palmer-2015a">{{Cite book |last=Palmer |first=Edwina |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rWzsCgAAQBAJ&dq=%22Kibi+clan%22&pg=PA71 |title=Harima Fudoki: A Record of Ancient Japan Reinterpreted, Translated, Annotated, and with Commentary |date=2015-11-09 |publisher=BRILL |isbn=978-90-04-26937-8 |language=en}}</ref>
Inami-no-Wakiiratsume, a woman from Inami, is mentioned in several ancient texts. She is thought to be the younger sister of Oiratsume from the "Kojiki,". She might have been a queen in Harima.<ref name="palmer-2015a" />
The Harima Fudoki does not mention Otarashihiko/Keiko as an emperor. Instead, Otarashihiko might have been a local leader in the Inami district of the Harima coast.<ref name="palmer-2015a" />
== Kibi clan rebellion == {{Main|Kibi Clan Rebellion}} The {{nihongo|Kibi Clan Rebellion|吉備氏の乱|kibishi no ran}} from 463 was a revolt against the [[Yamato Kingship|Yamato state]] on the [[Korean peninsula]], involving two brothers from the Kibi clan: Tasa and Oto. .<ref name="brinkley-p114">{{Harvnb|Brinkley|1915|p=114}}</ref><ref name="nihongi">{{cite book |last=Aston |first=William G. |url=https://jhti.berkeley.edu/Nihon%20shoki.html |title=Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697 |year=1896}}</ref>{{Sfn|Brinkley|1915|p=112}}<ref name="kamstra">{{cite book |last=Kamstra |first=Jacques H. |title=Encounter Or Syncretism: The Initial Growth of Japanese Buddhism |publisher=Brill Archive |year=1967 |page=255}}</ref>
The revolt was triggered when Tasa learned that the Japanese [[Emperor Yūryaku]] had moved him to the Japanese post at [[Mimana]] on the Korean Peninsula in order to seize his beautiful wife. The incident falls into Japan's [[Protohistory|proto-historic]] period and is recounted in the ''[[Nihon Shoki]]''.<ref name="brinkley-p114" /><ref name="nihongi" />{{Sfn|Brinkley|1915|p=112}}<ref name="kamstra" />
== Decline ==
In 713, at the suggestion of ''Bizen-no-kami'' Nanten - and ''Bizen-no-suke'' Kamitsukeno-no-Kenji the Eita, Katsuta, Tomata, Kume, Mashima, and Oba districts of [[Bizen Province]] were separated into a new province, and, and Kamitsukeno-no-Kenji was appointed as the first governor of [[Mimasaka Province]]. This separation was the final stage of the disintegration of the former [[Kingdom of Kibi]], and was intended to further weaken the Kibi clan by putting its iron resources directly under the control of the [[Imperial House of Japan|imperial government]].<ref>[http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/images/uploads/EOS070712Ab.pdf "Nationwide List of ''Ichinomiya''," p. 3] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130517061440/http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/images/uploads/EOS070712Ab.pdf|date=2013-05-17}}; retrieved 2012-11-20.</ref>
== In Popular culture == The Kibi clan features in [[Age of Empires (video game)|Age of Empires]] as an enemy faction alongside the [[Izumo clan]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Russell |first=Lawrence T. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IMDmDVRF7o0C&q=%22Kibi+clan%22 |title=Age of Empires: Unauthorized Game Secrets |date=1997 |publisher=Prima Pub. |isbn=978-0-7615-1053-6 |language=en}}</ref>
