The story of [[Emperor Keikō]] and Inami-no-Wakiiratsume in the [[Harima Fudoki]] shows the relationship between the Kibi clan and the [[Yamato Kingship]]. It suggests that the [[Inami, Hyōgo|Inami]] area was once a border between the Yamato and Kibi regions.<ref name="palmer-2015a">{{Cite book |last=Palmer |first=Edwina |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rWzsCgAAQBAJ&dq=%22Kibi+clan%22&pg=PA71 |title=Harima Fudoki: A Record of Ancient Japan Reinterpreted, Translated, Annotated, and with Commentary |date=2015-11-09 |publisher=BRILL |isbn=978-90-04-26937-8 |language=en}}</ref>

Inami-no-Wakiiratsume, a woman from Inami, is mentioned in several ancient texts. She is thought to be the younger sister of Oiratsume from the "Kojiki,". She might have been a queen in Harima.<ref name="palmer-2015a" />

The Harima Fudoki does not mention Otarashihiko/Keiko as an emperor. Instead, Otarashihiko might have been a local leader in the Inami district of the Harima coast.<ref name="palmer-2015a" />

== Kibi clan rebellion ==
{{Main|Kibi Clan Rebellion}}
The {{nihongo|Kibi Clan Rebellion|吉備氏の乱|kibishi no ran}} from 463 was a revolt against the [[Yamato Kingship|Yamato state]] on the [[Korean peninsula]], involving two brothers from the Kibi clan: Tasa and Oto. .<ref name="brinkley-p114">{{Harvnb|Brinkley|1915|p=114}}</ref><ref name="nihongi">{{cite book |last=Aston |first=William G. |url=https://jhti.berkeley.edu/Nihon%20shoki.html |title=Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697 |year=1896}}</ref>{{Sfn|Brinkley|1915|p=112}}<ref name="kamstra">{{cite book |last=Kamstra |first=Jacques H. |title=Encounter Or Syncretism: The Initial Growth of Japanese Buddhism |publisher=Brill Archive |year=1967 |page=255}}</ref>

The revolt was triggered when Tasa learned that the Japanese [[Emperor Yūryaku]] had moved him to the Japanese post at [[Mimana]] on the Korean Peninsula in order to seize his beautiful wife. The incident falls into Japan's [[Protohistory|proto-historic]] period and is recounted in the ''[[Nihon Shoki]]''.<ref name="brinkley-p114" /><ref name="nihongi" />{{Sfn|Brinkley|1915|p=112}}<ref name="kamstra" />

== Decline ==

In 713, at the suggestion of ''Bizen-no-kami'' Nanten - and ''Bizen-no-suke'' Kamitsukeno-no-Kenji the  Eita, Katsuta, Tomata, Kume, Mashima, and Oba districts of [[Bizen Province]] were separated into a new province, and, and Kamitsukeno-no-Kenji was appointed as the first governor of [[Mimasaka Province]]. This separation was the final stage of the disintegration of the former [[Kingdom of Kibi]], and was intended to further weaken the Kibi clan by putting its iron resources directly under the control of the [[Imperial House of Japan|imperial government]].<ref>[http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/images/uploads/EOS070712Ab.pdf "Nationwide List of ''Ichinomiya''," p. 3] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130517061440/http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/images/uploads/EOS070712Ab.pdf|date=2013-05-17}}; retrieved 2012-11-20.</ref>

== In Popular culture ==
The Kibi clan features in [[Age of Empires (video game)|Age of Empires]] as an enemy faction alongside the [[Izumo clan]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Russell |first=Lawrence T. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IMDmDVRF7o0C&q=%22Kibi+clan%22 |title=Age of Empires: Unauthorized Game Secrets |date=1997 |publisher=Prima Pub. |isbn=978-0-7615-1053-6 |language=en}}</ref>

